### Detailed Explanation of the Proof

The goal is to prove that `0 ≤ ‖eval (↑q) (X - C lamb)‖`. The norm of any element in a normed space is always non-negative. Therefore, the non-negativity of the norm of `eval (↑q) (X - C lamb)` directly follows from the properties of the norm. 

In Lean, `norm_nonneg` is a lemma that states that the norm of any element is non-negative. In this case, we apply it to `eval (↑q) (X - C lamb)`, which is an element of the appropriate type (here, `ℂ`, but Lean can generalize this to any normed additive group). 

Thus, the proof is straightforward and does not require any of the previous hypotheses. We simply invoke `norm_nonneg _`, where the `_` is inferred to be `eval (↑q) (X - C lamb)` based on the context.

